## Public Health and Societal Impact

### Safety and Mortality

Legal access to abortion significantly reduces maternal mortality and morbidity. The World Health Organization estimated that unsafe, illegal abortions cause approximately 68,000 maternal deaths annually worldwide. In countries where abortion is legal and regulated, the risk of death from abortion is less than 1 in 100,000, whereas the risk of death from childbirth is substantially higher (13.3 deaths per 100,000 pregnancies) ([Abortion and Women's Rights](https://abortionandcivilrights.weebly.com/pros-and-cons.html)).

Before Roe v. Wade (1973), illegal abortions were widespread in the U.S., with estimates ranging from 200,000 to 1.2 million annually, many performed under unsafe conditions. Legalization has allowed safer procedures and reduced complications such as septic abortion ([Cates et al., 2003](https://www.guttmacher.org/journals/psrh/2003/01/public-health-impact-legal-abortion-30-years-later)).

### Fertility and Birth Rates

Studies indicate that abortion legalization correlates with declines in birth rates, particularly among teenagers, unmarried women, and minority groups. For example, states legalizing abortion saw a 4% relative decline in fertility rates compared to those without changes in abortion laws. If abortion were recriminalized nationwide, an estimated 440,000 additional births per year could occur, impacting social services and economic conditions ([Joyce et al., 1990](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1508542/)).

### Socioeconomic Factors

Legal abortion can alleviate the burden on families struggling with poverty and inadequate resources. It allows women to avoid unwanted pregnancies that could exacerbate economic hardship and negatively affect child welfare. Denying abortion access disproportionately affects low-income women, who may resort to unsafe procedures or face lifelong consequences from forced motherhood ([KnowsWhy.com](https://www.knowswhy.com/why-should-abortion-be-legal/)).

