## Social and Legal Context

### Historical and Legal Background

The landmark 1973 Supreme Court decision Roe v. Wade established abortion as a constitutional right based on privacy rights implied by the 9th and 14th Amendments. Since then, abortion has remained legal federally, though states have enacted varying restrictions. The ongoing legal battles and recent Supreme Court cases (e.g., Dobbs v. Jackson Women's Health) continue to shape the landscape ([Academia.edu](https://www.academia.edu/1237734/Abortion_and_Womens_Rights_in_the_USA)).

### Access and Equality

Restricting abortion access often results in unequal outcomes based on socioeconomic status. Wealthier women can afford safe abortions, while poorer women may face dangerous alternatives. This disparity raises concerns about justice and equity in healthcare and reproductive rights ([KnowsWhy.com](https://www.knowswhy.com/why-should-abortion-be-legal/)).

